rmalized": false, "mention": "cancer", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9967124462127686, "span": {"begin": 1165, "end": 1171}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "tumor suppressor genes", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.8959261775016785, "span": {"begin": 1274, "end": 1296}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009369"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "tumor", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9683627486228943, "span": {"begin": 1274, "end": 1279}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cancer cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7887101173400879, "span": {"begin": 1298, "end": 1310}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009369"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cancer", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9988842606544495, "span": {"begin": 1298, "end": 1304}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cancer cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8424364924430847, "span": {"begin": 1451, "end": 1463}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009369"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cancer", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9959062337875366, "span": {"begin": 1451, "end": 1457}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cancer cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8187209963798523, "span": {"begin": 1581, "end": 1593}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009369"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cancer", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9997215867042542, "span": {"begin": 1581, "end": 1587}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cancer cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8064417839050293, "span": {"begin": 1678, "end": 1690}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009369"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cancer", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9995761513710022, "span": {"begin": 1678, "end": 1684}}, {"id": ["mesh:D010100"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "oxygen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.947790265083313, "span": {"begin": 1713, "end": 1719}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cancer cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7603832483291626, "span": {"begin": 1832, "end": 1844}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009369"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cancer", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9988594055175781, "span": {"begin": 1832, "end": 1838}}], "text": "Cancer is a general key event for related diseases each exhibiting uncontrolled proliferation of abnormal cells (for review see Hanahan and Weinberg 2011).&nbsp; A cancer often is initially associated with a specific organ, with malignant tumors developing ability to metastasize, or travel to other areas of the body.&nbsp; Most cancers develop from genetic mutations in normal cells; in this key event relationship we are focusing on disruption of apoptosis and necrosis pathways, leading to cancer.&nbsp;&nbsp; Exposure to chemical stressors, radiation, tobacco smoke, or viruses can increase the likelihood that cancer will develop.&nbsp; Pathways leading to apoptosis, or single cell death, have traditionally been studied as both independent and simultaneous from pathways leading to necrosis, or tissue-wide cell death, with both overlap and distinct mechanisms (Elmore 2007). For the purposes of this key event relationship, we are characterizing cancer due to widespread cell-death.   Cancer cells proliferate due to capabilities summarized by Hanahan and Weinberg (2011):     Sustained proliferation signaling &ndash; by deregulating normal cell signals, cancer cells can sustain chronic proliferation.  Evading growth suppressors &ndash; by evading activities of tumor suppressor genes, cancer cells continue to proliferate.  Activating invasion and metastasis &ndash; by altering shape and attachment to cells in the extracellular matrix, cancer cells gain ability to move to other locations.  Enabling replicative immortality &ndash; by disabling senescence pathways, cancer cells have extended lifespans.  Inducing angiogenesis &ndash; by enabling neovasculature, cancer cells receive nutrients and oxygen and get rid of waste products.  Resisting cell death &ndash; by evading apotosis and necrosis defense pathways, cancer cells avoid elimination.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 16:09:50 +0000 2026"}